The paper presents a distributed data processing platform for implementing graph mining algorithms, which is relevant to several sub-categories in computer science. cs.DB (databases) is a likely category as the paper deals with exploring a large number of subgraphs and finding patterns that match some criteria desired by the user. cs.DS (data structures and algorithms) is also a likely category as the paper presents algorithms for fundamental graph mining problems such as frequent subgraph mining, counting motifs, and finding cliques. cs.SI (social and information networks) is another likely category as the paper mentions the importance of these algorithms for social networks and semantic web. cs.LG (machine learning) is a possible category as the paper presents a high-level filter-process computational model that simplifies the development of scalable graph mining algorithms. cs.DC (distributed, parallel, and cluster computing) is also a possible category as the paper presents a distributed data processing platform for implementing graph mining algorithms.
